{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16104"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16104"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.41,0.25,0.16,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115197"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97205"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7061"},{"type":"tags","id":"8497"},{"type":"tags","id":"8499"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20997"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115197"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is examining a histological section of testicular tissue under light microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the microscopic appearance of Sertoli cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elongated cells with spindle-shaped nuclei at the tubule periphery","Columnar cells with pale irregular nuclei spanning basement to lumen","Rounded cells with dark nuclei clustered near the tubular centre","Polygonal cells with spherical nuclei between the tubules","Spherical cells with dense nuclei along the basement membrane"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct description is that Sertoli cells are \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolumnar cells with pale irregular nuclei spanning basement to lumen\u003C/strong\u003E. These cells are essential supporting cells within the seminiferous tubules that nurture developing sperm cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElongated cells with spindle-shaped nuclei at the tubule periphery\u003C/strong\u003E describes peritubular myoid cells, while \u003Cstrong\u003Erounded cells with dark nuclei clustered near the tubular centre\u003C/strong\u003E describes late-stage spermatids. \u003Cstrong\u003EPolygonal cells with spherical nuclei between the tubules\u003C/strong\u003E describes Leydig cells, and \u003Cstrong\u003Espherical cells with dense nuclei along the basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E describes spermatogonia. Sertoli cells have a distinctive histological appearance with their prominent nucleoli and pale, irregularly-shaped nuclei. They form tight junctions with adjacent Sertoli cells to create the blood-testis barrier and provide both structural and nutritional support to developing spermatogenic cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sertoli cells are tall columnar cells that extend from the basement membrane to the lumen of seminiferous tubules.","Sertoli cells have distinctive pale, irregularly-shaped nuclei with prominent nucleoli.","Sertoli cells provide structural and nutritional support to developing sperm cells within seminiferous tubules."],"references":["Lara NLEM, Costa GMJ, Figueiredo AFA, de Fran\u00e7a LR. The Sertoli cell: what can we learn from different vertebrate models? Anim Reprod. 2020 May 22;16(1):81-92. doi: 10.21451/1984-3143-AR2018-125. PMID: 33299481; PMCID: PMC7720927.","Wong WJ, Khan YS. Histology, Sertoli Cell. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560631/","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97205"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16104"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97205"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T09:46:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T09:48:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8795"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115197"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.e